{"kind":"article","sections":[],"seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Related Documentation","anchor":"Related-Documentation","identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ChoosingAnAPI","doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ForAIAgents"]},{"title":"Essentials","anchor":"Essentials","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ChoosingAnAPI"]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/sfsymbolskit\/typesafesymbols"]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","title":"Why Type-Safe Symbols","modules":[{"name":"SFSymbolsKit"}],"role":"article"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"The case for replacing stringly-typed SFSymbol names with compiler-checked properties."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Overview","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Every SFSymbol reference in an Apple-platform app passes through a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["Image(systemName: \"square.and.arrow.up\")","let icon = UIImage(systemName: \"gear\")"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"That string is never validated by the compiler. Three consequences follow, and all of them are maintenance costs that compound over the life of a codebase."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"No-autocomplete","text":"No autocomplete"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Xcode can’t suggest symbol names, because they aren’t part of your program — they’re opaque keys resolved at runtime. You context-switch to the SFSymbols app, search, copy, paste."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"No-compile-time-check","text":"No compile-time check"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\"gear\""},{"type":"text","text":" (valid) and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"\"gears\""},{"type":"text","text":" (not a symbol) are both just "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"type":"text","text":". The type system has nothing to verify against, so a typo is not a build error."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Silent runtime failure","anchor":"Silent-runtime-failure","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"UIImage(systemName:)"},{"type":"text","text":" returns "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"nil"},{"text":" for an unknown name; ","type":"text"},{"code":"Image(systemName:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" renders nothing. Neither throws. The bug ships, and the only signal is “the button looks wrong.”","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"The fix","anchor":"The-fix","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"SFSymbolsKit makes the catalog ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"data in your program"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":": a typed property per symbol, generated from Apple’s list. Autocomplete works, typos are compile errors, refactors are safe, and the whole catalog becomes enumerable.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["Image(systemName: String.SFSymbols.squareAndArrowUp)   \/\/ can't be misspelled"],"syntax":"swift"}],"kind":"content"}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/TypeSafeSymbols"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit"]]},"references":{"doc://com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit/documentation/SFSymbolsKit/ForAIAgents":{"title":"SFSymbolsKit for AI Coding Agents","identifier":"doc:\/\/com.spookylabs.SFSymbolsKit\/documentation\/SFSymbolsKit\/ForAIAgents","type":"topic","role":"article","abstract":[{"text":"Why SFSymbolsKit specifically solves a problem that AI coding assistants have with SFSymbols — and how an agent should use it.","typ